1. Definition
Hamming distance between two equal-length sequences is the number of positions at which corresponding symbols are different.

2. Formal definition and formula
Given two strings or vectors x and y of length n, HammingDistance(x,y) = sum_{i=0..n-1} [x[i] != y[i]] where [condition] is 1 when true, 0 when false.

3. Constraints and preconditions
- Inputs must have equal length; otherwise the Hamming distance is undefined. For strings, use Unicode code points as units when required.
- For binary/hamming-weight contexts, inputs are fixed-width bit-vectors.

4. Implementation notes (string vs bit-level)
- String-level: iterate code points (not UTF-16 code units) and compare code point values at each index; increment counter on mismatch.
- Bit-level: for integers, compute XOR of values and count set bits in result (see HAMMING_WEIGHT). Complexity O(n) where n is length in code points or O(b) for bit-width, dominated by popcount cost.

5. Supplementary details
- Use Unicode-aware iteration (for...of or codePointAt with manual indexing) to treat surrogate pairs as single code points.
- When working with Numbers vs BigInt, prefer BigInt for arbitrary large bit-width or when shifting beyond 32 bits.

6. Reference details (algorithms, complexity)
- String algorithm: for-of iteration over strings yields code point strings; compare with direct index access when iterating code points: index and codePointAt nextIndex to advance by 1 or 2 code units as needed.
- Bit algorithm: dist = popcount(a XOR b). popcount can be implemented with Kernighan's algorithm: while(x) { x &= x-1; count++ } with runtime proportional to number of set bits.

